Barack Obama will be the fourth President of the United States to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo for 26 hours as the fourth US president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
He will be awarded a diploma, a medal and a check worth $1.4 million, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen world diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of a committee that selected him from 172 people and 33 organizations in October.
The presidential couple are then scheduled to meet with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the award, but only the third to receive it in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war when accepting the award.
The president does not want to avoid this topic, because he realizes that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
The war effort was further intensified a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to emphasize.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate to charity, but has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The busy program will then take the president and his wife to a banquet where, in addition to the King and Queen of Norway, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests will be invited.
From the beginning, Obama has been rather restrained about the price.
He said, for example, that he feels that he does not fully deserve it.
He also reiterated several times that the prize is not just for him, but for all who strive for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he said it was a "call to action" for him.
