USA: Repeat is the mother of wisdom
It is ridiculous how hard Barack Obama, a president with a reputation for being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the dumbest, in the Afghan question.
When he finally sweated out his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it from Bush’s Iraqi script three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate even to use the title of Bush's January 2007 declaration as the title of his own declaration: "A new way forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to a civil war-torn Iraq as an “irresponsible and catastrophic decision.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of the field commanders, was the only one possible and highly successful, so much so that there is no mention of Iraq in the news today.
It did not improve Bush's reputation, but objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting position than one might expect.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the hesitant shooters at the White House, despite subordinate customs.
He asked for 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze out the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally counted at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in as little as 18 months and to end the process in three years.
Many doubt that a halved increase will yield the same fruit as the Iraq process.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied on and no agreements are respected.
Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing masters every day as they please, are poorly prepared under these conditions.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain just a Potemkin village, behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the vagueness of the situation, which is further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even building an “accessible state”, which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, does not seem very realistic.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy strikes with its voluntarism.
The situation in Afghanistan has only deteriorated over the past eight years and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent to the war turmoil for the purpose of "swift return home" will work a miracle here, can only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will perceive it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to take part in combat operations in Afghanistan is dwindling.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy relates to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and heightened sanctions do not impress the Iranians, the United States will face an overwhelming question as to whether or not to try to resolve the problem by military force.
It will have to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America will proceed to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only plaster for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election, and therefore there is enough time left for him to come up with another strategy if this turns out to be a total failure.
