The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the Academy of Sciences of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metallocarborates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists have come up with new ‘enhanced’ compounds prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to a viral protein.
Metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are bound together by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Treacherous and Resistant Virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is necessary for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by the cleavage of HIV, mature infectious viral particles would not have formed.
When we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is further systematically altered.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in a tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metallocarborates on a common enzyme variant is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and also their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical treatments thus make metallocarborates interesting compounds for further research aimed at the design of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina <0xC5><0x98>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology and Institute of Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry.
