In aging China, a change of course
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters reading “Mother Earth is too exhausted to feed more children” and “One more child means one more grave.”
Then they learned that when official government posts in Shanghai, alarmed by the low birth rate and aging population in their city, suddenly changed course this summer and began to encourage young couples, their reaction was immediate and determined: Never.
We have always devoted all our time and energy to one child.
We didn’t save anything for others, says Wang, 31, a HR manager who has an 8-month-old son.
China’s more than 30-year-old policy of having only one child was introduced, creating two generations of only notorious chubby and pampered children, affectionately nicknamed “little emperors,” a country threatened by a population crisis.
The average birth rate fell to 1.8 children per couple, compared to six before the policy went into effect, according to UN data.
The distribution of the population, where the population aged 60 years and above is predicted to skyrocket from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050, far above the overall average of around 20 percent.
The imbalance is greater in wealthy coastal cities with populations with higher education, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for almost 22 percent of Shanghai’s registered population, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, director of the Shanghai City Commission on Population and Family Planning, said many couples must have children to “help reduce the proportions of the aging population and reduce the number of the workforce in the future.”
He says it's about "being old, it's not about being rich -- like in developed countries like Japan or Sweden."
Gradual soothing
As enshrined in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial mandate introduced under the Communist Party.
Couples who violated politics faced enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some areas -- and discrimination at work.
China’s official sites promoted policies that helped the country prevent critical exploitation of natural resources, while human rights defenders were condemned in advancing the policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women to have abortions on their second child.
In addition, many couples had to undergo sexist selective abortions, leading to an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, population officials have been gradually moderated in their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they generally allowed exceptions -- including city dwellers, members of national minorities, and cases where a man and a woman were single children -- and in 2007 they eased the diction of their hardline slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University’s Institute of Population Research, said central government officials had previously debated more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners was an only child.
In June, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage more births.
Almost overnight, posters urging parents to have only one child were replaced by copies of the regulation detailing how to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city government sent family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples in their homes and put leaflets under the door.
They also promised to provide emotional and financial advice to those who decided to have more than one child.
The reaction was cold, family planning officials said.
Annoying response
While officials in a rural city around Shanghai have seen an increase in interest in couples wishing to have a second child after the campaign began, most city districts have not reported changes.
Huinan City District, with a population of 115,000, for example, still registered four to five cases per month.
Disappointed officials in Shanghai said that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city is still expected to be only around 165,000 in 2010 - slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai’s Caolu district, said financial considerations were probably the main reason people didn’t want to have more children.
They want to give the best to the first child, he said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said she would like to have two children and they were legally allowed to do so.
But like many Chinese, who only have insufficient health and life insurance, provided by the government.
Without a vital interceptor network, the choice could be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a contentious legal issue, says Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is in a relationship with her first child in the seventh month of pregnancy.
Yes, we were deprived of the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just in politics.
It's about the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons for hesitation.
Wang, a HR manager, says they only want one child because she was also an only child: “We were the center of attention of our families and everyone took care of us.
We weren’t used to providing care, and in fact we didn’t want to worry about others.
Chen Zijian, 42, who runs a translation company, expressed this much more openly.
For two-career middle-class parents who have reduced birth rates, he said, being successful means being selfish.
Today’s 20- and 30-year-olds see their parents as the breakthrough of the early days of the Chia experiment with capitalism, and they don’t want this way of feeding themselves, he says.
One child puts enormous demands on the time of parents, he says.
A mother must sacrifice at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the questions of the space -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and the strategy -- "You have to have your resume ready by the time the child is 9 months old for good preschool education.
