The United Nations has outlined a plan to reduce emissions.
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by far-reaching unruly stances and mutual slander -- re-focused Friday on releasing a document proposing ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years with industrialized nations bearing most of the burden in the near future.
The text, which can provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, highlights the remaining obstacles as well as illuminates the way forward.
But important progress was seen in the negotiations that took place at the wrong time with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Created by the UN ad hoc task force, this text discreetly sets out how much money rich countries should provide to those poor to deal with global warming in the short and long term.
And it provides a full palette of choices for key issues, including how to develop and manage emerging economies to limit their carbon emissions, and what the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers will still be able to tolerate should be.
This adds a lot of flexibility to the process, says John Coequyt, chief executive of the Washington Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutjajar, who proposed the six-page document, a 180-page briefing from the meeting to focus on what UN climate chief Yvo de Boer described as a "big picture".
It outlines the outlines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations could collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent within a year compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent during that period.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union urgently discussed on Friday a pledge to provide $3.6 trillion over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to climate change -- from managing floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
But Friday still featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that dominated last week’s talks.
U.S. Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern rejected a speech calling for binding greenhouse gas emission reductions for industrialized countries compared to volunteering for major emerging economies if they were not funded by the developed world.
The shift signaled that the Obama administration had set a tougher line against China by Bush administration officials just two years ago.
The United States will not agree to the treaty without transferring major developing countries and carrying out actions, Stern said, also complaining that the text was insufficient to secure restrictions and should be reviewed by external observers.
Stern made the comment an hour after Chinese deputy foreign secretary He Yafei told a U.S. chief negotiator on climate issues that either a lack of “peasant reason” or “extraordinary irresponsibility” led earlier in the week to the message that the United States would not help China financially to deal with global issues.
With the future of the economic trajectory of the world’s major powers at stake, tensions have broken out both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current struggle is mostly about preserving individual economies rather than preserving the planet, between China and the United States for fulfilling their respective commitments, while poorer nations point out that two dozen of the world’s most influential countries ignore the scientific imperative to take more forceful action.
Ricardo Ulate, Costa Rica’s delegate, said it’s not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the cost of cutting greenhouse gases, while vulnerable countries have become much more aggressive in finding a way to prevent large issuers from acting responsibly in their actions.
It’s clearly a game of having a new economic hegemony unfold, said Ulate, who also serves as a regional adviser on regional climate change in Mexico and Central America for international conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the effects of climate change have indicated they would like to continue pushing for a legally binding agreement in Copenhagen, but most of the main participants said a political agreement would be the best outcome of the talks.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, created a 24-page draft agreement last Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who led the international climate talks on behalf of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations "has caused a political turmoil for the entire political process" in part because they are now united and demand action from growing economies such as China and India.
The negotiations sparked a new urgency once the delegates focused on the fact that they had to resolve most of the remaining contentious issues before the heads of government competed for an agreement.
High-ranking officials such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Deputy Minister got off the planes and ran through Bella Center halls to the closed doors of meetings and new conferences so they could set out the claims to be assessed next week.
The sheer scale of the gathering – with 13,000 people moving daily from and to the convention center, guitar-playing activists staged at night ironic spectacles about the countries they thought had sent them out, hand-to-hand submissions on paper rather than e-mail – driven by a challenge.
The intensity is just a superstructure: almost all key ministers were present in Copenhagen, and earlier on Wednesday 60 heads of state.
“We’ve gotten into high categories,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Deputy Minister of Global Policy for International Nature Conservation.
Heavy weights are coming.
