His move gained the support of Hervé de Charett (formerly for-UMP now for NC), who claimed ownership of the UDF brand as the first to have it registered with the National Institute of Industrial Property (l'Institut national de la propriété industrielle) in 2004.
But on Friday evening, a committee of the UDF Association led by friends of François Bayrou, who do not intend to be expropriated, stepped out of its silence and filed a formal request to the minister and MPs to stop using the abbreviation and hand back ownership of the trademark, under threat of criminal prosecution.
In recent days, you have raised alarming statements about proposing to your political movement to +retake+ the abbreviation UDF, the Association writes in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the committee, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez from the MoDem party or Senator Jean Arthuis of the Alliance center.
At the same time, you considered it appropriate to place on your promotional materials and on the welcome website of your movement the name+Nouveau centre+, with the slogan +UDF today+, the signatories of the letter also note.
As you know, you have no right to use this abbreviation, the UDF Committee explains, asking the NC movement to “immediately remove all references to the UDF name from all promotional materials, including (its) websites.”
It also asks Hervé de Charette "to transfer the ownership of the trademark to the legitimate owners".
If you do not, we will go to the courts to ensure that the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members are respected.
In their letter, they state that the UDF "has been a full-fledged political movement since 1978" and recall that Mr. Morin and his friends "choose" to leave in 2007 "to create a competitive movement, like others in 2002, to establish the UMP.
According to them, the Nouveau centre has no right to use the abbreviation UDF (Union pour la démocratie française).
At the same time, they recall that the last UDF congress in 2007 voted to join the MoD for three years and to create a committee tasked with defending the "moral and material interests" of the association founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the committee continues, "when he registered the mark", he was "not a member of the UDF for three years, but of the UMP.
In a scandalous and fraudulent way, he used a non-existent acronym registration to do so at his own expense.
This intactness begins to turn into a crime, they claim, and then ironically comment on NC’s strategy: “It seems to us that both in politics and in everyday life it is more valuable to make a name for oneself than to step out of anonymity by fraudulently adopting a name to which we have no right.”
