The Managerial Revolution or the End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been useless.
For more than a decade, the behavior of the management of large companies towards employees has been reminiscent of the attitude of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees identify with the “values” determined from the mountain, as it used to be, when it was necessary to impose on the consumer products that came from the ideas of the heads of factory technicians.
By becoming the center of business companies, the marketing revolution has aligned the strategy of conquering the market in the right direction...although authoritarian efforts to impose products other than customer preferences are regularly coming back!
The passive attitude of employees can lead to fatal demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just a visible part of a much more widespread general phenomenon that affects mostly managerial staff.
This demobilization adversely affects the development of all intellectual functions of society, including research and development, and more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI “requires from all stakeholders (...) an active approach and the ability to anticipate” and requires from employees commitments that are completely at odds with the revenues of authoritarian management.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that aims to put employees at the center of the company’s interest as well as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls.
Will internal opinion polls – such as a questionnaire submitted to Orange employees – contribute to a revolution in management practices?
I'm afraid not.
Mainly because I have already convinced myself that in the face of the new situation, the structure will return, after various turns, to what it has always done!
Furthermore, authoritarianism, as one of the pathologies of power, increases in proportion to the severity of its own failures.
Finally, because most executives have a simplified view of human behavior.
Because they are graduates of engineering colleges, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
For the sake of convenience, they are adopting an old behaviorist theory, now revived by “neurologists” from the US and widely disseminated without much knowledge of scientific institutes and the media.
The fact that it is possible to move the "levers" (sic) of the involvement of managers, showed a recent survey by the agency Ipsos on the site Figaro.fr, which only confirms the managers in their position of mechanical control, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors.
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises presupposes the adoption of a final vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating a basic insight into all the intentions and practices of management: For employees, commitments to the company will only be possible if they appear to be a clear means of achieving their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Currently, this concept of employee motivation is dealt with only by studies of Motivational Functional Analysis.
These studies have shown that they evaluate their businesses on the basis of a predetermined dox, which will allow them, through the image that speaks about the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life goals.
By identifying and measuring these mobilization factors, managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and put their HR management "on the right track".
This creates a breeding ground for the development of solid and effective economic intelligence.
With his speech in Oslo: “A Just War,” Obama won praise from the right.
The U.S. right welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize winner had defended the concept of a "just war" against enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who initially mocked Obama’s Oct. 9 award, applauded the presidential speech this time, including Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Palin, the muse of the right-wing Republican wing, to USA Today, adding that she herself expressed herself on the topic of the "sometimes necessary" war in her memoirs, which are just coming out.
War is, of course, the last thing Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
All terrorists should be detained there, he believes.
President Obama, who inherited two wars in Afghanistan and Iraq from his predecessor George W. Bush, justified the deployment of forces in Oslo on Thursday and used the speech to clarify his decision to send another 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I think that the speech was really very good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives congratulated, acknowledging above all the President's mention of "the existence of evil in the world".
In a way, I considered this speech to be completely historical, Gingrich said during an interview on the radio program "The Takeaway".
The former MP, who is considered by some to be a possible Republican candidate in the 2012 presidential election, was excited to see a "left-wing president" reminding Nobel committee members that they themselves would not be free and could not hand over the Peace Prize if the use of force did not exist.
According to Michael Gerson, former speechwriter George W. Bush, now editor of the Washington Post, Obama delivered a “very American speech.”
Not only did he present himself as a “world citizen” as always, but he “speaked like an American president” and reminded Europeans “that they live in a safe bubble that they did not create themselves and that they are not doing too much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the few right-wing dissatisfied are Bush-era hawk, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, who described the speech as “uniform, pompous and uninspired,” according to the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, for example, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich is horrified to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
“When we wrap war in the envelope of justice, we can easily justify the massacre of innocent people,” he said.
However, the middle-left press takes a commendable stance on the president.
Although the Los Angeles Times continues to view the awarding of the peace prize to Obama as premature, it has rated his performance as "overpowering", even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech should serve as a guide to international decision-making in conflict resolution, the fight against poverty and oppression.”
Obama “made the speech that was needed,” the New York Times said, calling the speech “simple and instructive.”
