The Turkish judiciary has dissolved for the Kurdish side, and this decision carries dire consequences.
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday ruled on the abolition of the main pro-Kurdish party in the country. This decision immediately sparked protests and demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to lend a friendly hand to the Kurdish community in an attempt to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) has been disbanded as it has become a “nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity,” Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was unanimously passed by 11 judges, where a majority of seven votes was needed to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and lawmaker Aysely Tugluková, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Mrs Tuglukova and the confiscation of the party’s assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP party has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
The party’s leadership warned before the verdict that MEPs would rather leave Parliament than serve as MEPs without political affiliation.
The decision is a continuation of a trial launched in 2007 by Cassation Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, accusing the DTP of obeying the “orders” of the Kurdistan Workers’ Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries regard as a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political showcase for the PKK rebels.
The party says it has no "fundamental connection" with the PKK, but refuses to identify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict comes as the government extends a friendly hand to the Kurdish community and offers a series of measures to strengthen their rights, and tries to curb Kurdish support for the PKK to end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a resumption of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations have erupted in recent weeks against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan is detained in clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of protesters have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast that is mostly inhabited by Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or shot rocks with slingshots.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said the justice decision would only "promote desperation".
Turkey cannot resolve this issue by banning the party, he said in a press release.
The government, made up of the party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are against the principle of cancellation of parties.
This is not the case, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a complete blowout of the democratic proposals initiated by the government, commented the political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can wait for the reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, killing seven soldiers three days earlier.
