The Cradle of Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-high animal ran over two powerful hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelimbs with sickle-tailed claws, and a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in the Thursday issue of the journal Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily traits.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then located in the equatorial dry region of the supercontinent Pangea.
Tawa opens a new window on the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship, distribution and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
“Sometimes we find a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments,” said team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The finding confirms theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are very rare, usually only fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is generally questionable.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards were divided into three most important developmental lines: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyrannosaurus rex, Velociraptor, as well as birds, "long-necked" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and herbivorous animals such as Ornithistors and Trinithistors.
Tawa hallae is the original terapod after the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues.
It exhibits an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, researchers found evidence of air bags, which even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related lineage of giant sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, he created this useful innovation probably already a common ancestor of both groups.
At least three migrant waves to North America
Since the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists concluded that lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development soon split and spread from South America to all the continents that then, as the supercontinent Pangaea, formed a single Earth mass.
The team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related, theropods.
The three cannot come from one common, migratory ancestor, scientists argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His conjecture could bring together a distorted picture, as many primitive dinosaur fossils have survived in South America, and they are rarely found on other continents.
As the dinosaurs have shown that they evolved from a relatively rare secondary lineage of the reptile genus to the ruling vertebrates on earth during the Earth's Middle Ages, it remains a mystery.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flying lizards, and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species evolved, while relatives became extinct and the interface between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
The success story didn’t last forever.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction, which the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but not the reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better, so they could squeeze out the competition.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, the impact helped another group of animals that also evolved in the Triassic and have lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
