Worlds of Dreams
Some see images in the waking state and hear voices that others cannot see or hear.
It is not only the mentally ill or drug addicted who draw the line between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything is fine.
If we lie with our eyes closed in our dark room, we can surround ourselves with the wildest imaginations and fantasies.
But those who experience dream states in their wakefulness, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, in today’s Western world they tend to think of themselves as crazy or drug addicts, or at least as strange.
However, such images and voices do not arise only in the mentally ill or in drug addiction.
The same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings, or write novels make sure that the boundaries between dream, imagination, and reality are merged here and there.
Dreams altered state of consciousness can occur in a variety of forms, at best called visions, at worst delusions.
Although the initiator and effect may differ, the visions of mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the shamanic states of delusions, psychoses and hallucinations can be derived from similar processes.
Hallucinations or visions arise when the balance of the brain’s neuronal transmitters – primarily dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin, and acetylcholine – is derailed and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusions occur very often in schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over it.
The connection between delusion and dream has occupied philosophers and physicians since antiquity.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of dreaming in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychology, stated in 1861 "the great similarity of delirium with dream states", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "psychosis, with all nonsense, delusions, delusions of the senses".
