In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fears and the deepest doubts, he says.
Ghosts are a terrible reality.
About one percent of people get schizophrenia at least once in a lifetime, in psychiatric clinics it is the second most frequently treated disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most people with disabilities can no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, and they get into an over-awakened state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship illusions or the illusion of persecution.
Hearing voices – voices that command, comment, or conduct dialogues – is particularly common.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is unable to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain is unable to filter out disturbing signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens up a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
Perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the University of Heidelberg’s General Psychiatry Clinic.
The schizophrenic is at the center of everything, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he becomes, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is not usually possible with them, ghosts are a terrible reality, awakening is excluded.
Once in a lifetime to experience a hallucination
Otherwise than in a dream, says Fuchss, "the sensory and spatial structure of reality, which one perceives in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience occurs within a real framework.
Scientists still face a riddle as to why our brains are doing this kind of sweep.
Exceptional states can lead everyone to lose touch with reality in the short term, Fuchs says.
Not everyone develops into a psychotic.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Scientists believe that the affected people have minimal brain damage.
It is believed that neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged at an early stage of development, for example, by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery as to how a neuronal system disorder will occur, which has not manifested itself for many years.
The role is also played by environmental influences - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if there is a disposition to it.
Also, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis, as they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brains are boiling
Crazy is that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations, and to get rid of them, they swallow expensive drugs, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in the book "Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf".
Hallucinations belong to the typical accompanying phenomena of psychoses, but also to surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, illnesses such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s or brain trauma are also common.
Surprisingly, even the brain of a healthy person hallucinates under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or little suppressed; when our brain is boiling or when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries with love or other other exceptional states.
In recent studies, up to a third of those surveyed reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
