This shy girl is considered a tight-knit dreamer, but Sarah K. does not dream, she knows it.
He's awake, he hears and sees the boy, just like he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him in the bench.
He can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? he asks sometimes.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night the appearances are rather depressing
Often, delusions are a burden.
As she sits in the classroom, she can’t watch the lesson how many times, because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just presenting a new classmate, but he explains to everyone else audible and visible on the board of mathematical equations.
At night, the appearances are rather depressing.
When he waits in his dark room for sleep, which comes rarely and too late, he is often unable to distinguish whether he is awake or already asleep, whether the images he sees, grimaces, or a girl with bleeding cuts on her hands and feet, arise before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he's yelling at the characters.
She doesn't tell her parents and friends about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she hasn’t gone crazy.
Delusions are also the art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or is deprived of stimuli, they will be more likely to have hallucinations, says Kasten.
I believe that the brain does not have enough work and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, as a little girl, was afraid of other children, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man she calls dad since she thought for herself was not her own father.
Because in visual and acoustic hallucinations, the same brain regions that process real perceptions and sounds are active, it is difficult for afflicted people like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that make the brain work, which is why it acts so real.”
Also night dreams are evaluated by Kasten as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations in healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Therefore, Kasten advises his patients to evaluate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our world too focused on awareness, the imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic of the Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a difficult, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - the illusion is also the art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard investigated the so-called oneiroid form of experience, a special form of altered dream consciousness.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the person considers real and cannot even distinguish them from the waking state.
Oneiroid state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or disease, for example, patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis at full consciousness.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and of himself, for example by a persistent, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline state between a dream and a hallucination.
Since it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, the worlds will change, but the real situation will be present in the imagination.
An intense form of sensory support and sensory transference in some unbearable situation that allows people’s own ability to form, to pass in an instant into a loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Also, art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" (The Exchange of Hearts) as a rescue action of the soul.
He was 49 years old when, after a heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness went on a several-day journey, while his body lay motionless in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he had created, visiting alien times and places: becoming an old man confined to a bed, in a train sanatorium, a robot watching over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility who make narcotics out of blood.
On a motorcycle, he is abducted by a Greek man to his homeland, surfing on a hotbed in the Alps on a hospital bed, and meets a Korean mobster.
It dives completely into the imaginary story, everything is real, even later in the memories.
These inner paths are fundamentally different for Claussen from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes its experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear after years and in unimportant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the actual experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other real experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, oneiroid states, psychoses, hallucinations and drug intoxication show how fragile even in the waking state our inner images of external reality are.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, “can lead to a distortion of what we call reality.”
A fact that can also be enriching.
