75% of working mothers have work-related maternity problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among women of younger age who are planning to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and careers of Spanish women', conducted by CSIC in cooperation with the Women's Institute.
The study involved 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study highlights that at the beginning of a partnership cohabitation there are many differences in views on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, as well as on the type of work.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, start living with a partner earlier, give birth to their first child earlier and have more children overall.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have their first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted most of their life to achieving their stable employment and therefore had to postpone the cohabitation of partners and the arrival of children.
The type of occupation also has a strong impact on maternity, although it has a minor impact on the time it takes to start cohabiting with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage andthe birth of a child is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the level of education, the higher the age at which women get married and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35 to 49, women with primary and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their level of education.
Women with primary education marry and give birth to their first child before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education prefer to get a stable job before marrying and having their first child,” Delgado said.
