The handbrake assistance system is already a mandatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-lock system, it will also be with ESP stability control, handbrake assist systems, all this will become a mandatory equipment for European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others a deadline is set for the elimination of the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase the protection of pedestrians, while working in a way that can help prevent many collisions.
The handbrake assist system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver pushes.
However, it is not always possible to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the car parts manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not press the brake before a collision, and half of them did not use the full brake force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires maximum from the braking system, shortening the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 pedestrian-related fatalities per year could be avoided.
Reducing this number would be even more striking—according to calculations, one in four accidents with an impact on people would be avoided—after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, in addition to light braking.
If the driver reacts, it will help to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if a collision cannot be avoided, the device will affect the brakes as intensely as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
